    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-03-23T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-03-23T10:00:00-05:00" n="348"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/585: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-03-23T10:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 23, 1920—10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 24—4:03 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>55. Minister for Foreign Affairs made reply last night to Bolivian note of March
                        16,<note n="85" xml:id="d348fn85">Bolivian note of Mar. 16 was in reply to
                        the Peruvian counter-reply of Mar. 6 referred to in the Chargé’s telegram
                        no. 46, Mar. 5, <ref target="#pg_328">p. 328</ref>.</note> reaffirming
                    position of Peru. He stated to me that this was the last reply he was sending to
                    Bolivia as there was nothing more to be said by Peru. All agitation has ceased
                    and perfect calm prevails in Peru.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
